1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {Although this move defies the chess
laws [i.e bringing the queen out as early as on the fourth move], Black cannot
exploit it. Despite the fact that this move was reasonably often played in the
past, we shall deal with an even rarer continuation in this database.} Nc6 (
4... e5 {I do not think this move will have many followers since it weakens
the d5 square for no reason}) (4... Bd7 {This move is aimed to prevent White
from playing Bb5 when Black plays Nc6. However, to Black's disappointment our
intention is to play Qe3 in response to Nc6 and so this move is just a waste
of time.}) (4... a6 {Even this move is aimed against 5.Bb5 and so we should
not have any problem as Black simply lost a tempo.}) (4... Nf6 {This is an
interesting move order against 5.Bb5. However, we should not have any worries
as the play more or less transposes to the main line.}) 5. Qe3 {I prefer this
move because it is a relatively fresh concept and there is no need to memorize
a huge number of lines. Moreover, this variation will be even more helpful in
shorter time controls due to the simplicity of the position and White's next
moves are more or less predictable: Be2, 0-0 followed by c4 and b3. The move
h2-h3 is optional in the opening phase. It is more important for White to
understand the middlegame plans and nuances than the opening theory since not
many games have been played in the variation I suggest. It is therefore
recommended to study the model games in depth and only then move on to the
theory section.} (5. Bb5 {is perfectly playable and has been played many times
over the years.}) *

