{[#]} 10... Ne8 {Black wants to play e5 followed by Nd4, taking advantage of
the fact that the queen is on e3 instead of the bishop. However, Black's plan
has a strategic flaw:} (10... Be6 {[%emt 0:00:03] This was analysed in model
game}) 11. b3 {White continues to play the logical developing moves.} e5 12.
Rd1 Nd4 $2 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Rxd4 $1 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 $18 {Apart from the
dangerous a1-h8 diagonal, White also has the d5 outpost for his knight which
soon proves to be fatal for Black. White kept playing logical moves one after
the other to take home the full point.} Nc7 (15... Qf6 16. Qd2 {[%cal Gc1b2,
Ra1h8,Yc3d5]}) (15... f6 16. Nd5 Be6 17. Bh6 Rf7 18. Nb6 Rb8 19. Rd1 $18 {
[%csl Gb6,Rb8,Rf7,Gh6][%cal Rh6f8]}) 16. Bb2 Ne6 17. Qd2 {[%cal Rc3d5]} f6 18.
Nd5 Nc7 19. Nb6 {[%csl Gb6] A knight on the 6th rank is usually a headache for
your opponent!} Rb8 20. Rd1 {White develops all his pieces first before taking
any concrete actions} Be6 21. Qf4 Ne8 22. c5 {[%cal Rd1d8]} Qc7 23. Bg4 $1 {
Trading White's inactive piece for the opponent's active defender. After the
bishop exchange, the knight on d5 will be a monster.} Bxg4 24. hxg4 Rf7 25. Nd5
Qxc5 26. Qd2 Rd8 27. Rc1 Qa7 28. Bd4 Qb8 29. Rc3 $1 {White does not hurry and
gradually increases the pressure.} Rdd7 (29... Rc8 30. Ba7 $1) 30. Qc1 {A queen
behind the rook is often a deadly combination!} Nc7 31. Nxf6+ Rxf6 32. Bxf6 Rf7
33. e5 d5 34. e6 Rxf6 35. Rxc7 Rf8 36. Qc5 Re8 37. Qd6 d4 38. Qd7 {
Navara-Johnson 1-0 2018} *

