{[#]} 9... Nd7 {Black not only wants to play Nc5, but he can also change his
plan by playing Nde5 to exchange the f3 knight and then to take control of the
d4-square. On the other hand, White's knight can jump to d5 and Black has to
make some sort of concession in order to challenge it.} 10. Rb1 {This move is
more or less automatic whenever Black plays Nd7 since White can respond with
b4 whenever Black plays Nc5. The rook on b1 is also useful in defending the
bishop after it moves to b2.} Nde5 11. O-O O-O (11... Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Nd4 13.
Rd1 (13. b3 {is also possible}) 13... Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 {[%cal Rc4c5]} Bd7 (14...
O-O 15. c5 $16) 15. Be3 $14 {[%cal Ge3d4] Followed by Bd4}) 12. Rd1 Nxf3+ 13.
Bxf3 f5 {From Black's perspective this move makes a lot of sense because Black
can develop his bishop with tempo if White takes on f5 since the rook is on b1.
That being said, this move also weakens the e6-square after a possible
exchange of the light-squared bishops.} 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Bd5+ {A useful
intermediate check since it drives the king to the corner.} (15. Be4 Qd7 16.
Nd5 {[%cal Rd5b6]} (16. b3 {fails to} Bxc3 $17) 16... Qe6 $1 17. Bxf5 Qxf5 $132
{Svidler-Karjakin 0-1 2015}) 15... Kh8 16. Be4 Qd7 17. b3 Qe6 (17... Bxc3 18.
Qxc3+ {[%cal Rc3h8]}) 18. Bb2 $14 *

