{[#]} 21... Qxf5 {It is always better to move the rook from the a1-h8 diagonal}
22. Rac1 {[%cal Ye3a7]} (22. Bd4 $6 e5 $1 23. Bxa7 e4 $132 {[%cal Re4f3,Rg7a1]}
) 22... b6 23. Nd5 Qd7 (23... Bxd5 24. Rxd5 Qf7 25. a4 $16 {[%csl Ga4,Ra7,Gb3,
Rb6,Gc4,Rd6,Re7] Although the Black bishop is controlling the long diagonal it
neither attacks nor threatens anything and so it would be wiser for White to
exchange it only when it is absolutely necessary.}) 24. Qh4 {Forcing Black to
take on d5} Bxd5 (24... Re8 25. Bg5 $16) 25. Rxd5 $16 {This is the dream
position for White when Black plays f5 as an attempt to create attacking
chances. Here the light squares have been seriously weakened and White will
exploit that fact by playing on the light squares, especially e4 and d5. The
rest of the game is a matter of simple technique.} Rf8 26. Qe4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4]}
Rae8 27. Rcd1 Rf5 28. a4 {[%csl Ra7,Rb6,Ge3] A useful move as it fixes the
weakness.} Bf6 29. Rxf5 gxf5 30. Qd5+ Kh8 31. g4 fxg4 32. hxg4 Rg8 33. Kg2 Qe8
34. Qf5 Qg6 35. Rd5 Qxf5 36. Rxf5 Kg7 37. a5 bxa5 38. Rxa5 Rb8 39. Rb5 Ra8 40.
Rb7 a5 41. g5 Bc3 42. Rxe7+ Kg8 43. Ba7 Bd2 44. Bd4 Rb8 45. Rg7+ Kf8 46. Rxh7 {
Ni Hua-Zhou Jianchao 2009 1-0} *

