{[#]} 10... b6 $6 {This move was not necessary to play at this moment.} (10...
Rc8 {was preferable. However, White is better anyway.}) 11. Rd1 Rc8 12. Rb1 {
[%cal Gb2b3] A necessary move before playing b3.} (12. b3 Nxe4) 12... Nh5 {
Doomed to passivity, Black tries to open up the position by playing f5.} 13. b3
f5 14. Bb2 Qe8 (14... f4 {Black should play like this only when he can push
his kingside pawns by means of g5 and h5. Here Black is lacking several tempi
in order to achieve this and White is in time to break through in the centre
to open up the position.} 15. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Gc3d5]}) 15. Nd5 $1 $14 {A
typical move, opening up the position in White's favor.} fxe4 16. Ng5 (16. Qxe4
$2 {runs into} Bf5 $17) 16... Bxb2 (16... Bh6 17. h4 $16 {[%csl Gb2,Gd5,Gg5]
[%cal Ra1h8]}) 17. Rxb2 Ng7 18. g4 {There was no need to weaken his kingside.}
({Simple play gives White a huge advantage.} 18. Nxe4 Nf5 19. Qc3 $16) 18...
Ne5 19. Nxe4 Bc6 20. f4 {All of Black's pieces are pushed backwards and White
is clearly on top as Black failed to generate counterplay.} Nd7 21. Bf1 $1 {
[%cal Gb2g2,Gb2f2] Clearing the path for the White rook along the second rank.}
Bxd5 {Black could not find any other way to keep the game going.} 22. cxd5 {
[%csl Rc6][%cal Gf1b5,Gb5c6]} Nf6 {White is having more space and so it is
logical to maintain more pieces instead of exchanging them. White effortlessly
managed to win the game.} 23. Nc3 Qd7 24. Rg2 Kh8 25. Ba6 Rc7 26. b4 e6 27.
dxe6 Qxe6 28. Qd4 h5 29. Re2 Qg8 30. g5 Rxc3 31. Qxc3 Nd5 32. Rxd5 Qxd5 33. Re7
Qg8 34. Qd4 Re8 35. Rxa7 Ra8 36. Bc4 Rxa7 37. Bxg8 Kxg8 38. Qxb6 Rxa2 39. Qxd6
Kh7 40. b5 {Kovalev-Golubka 2019 1-0} *

