{The position is balanced. Both sides have no weaknesses. White has a space
advantage but should watch out for b6-b5 breaks. Black does not have any other
plan than that and should simply wait and see how White continues with his
play.} 14... Ba8 {[%cal Yb6b5] Black keeps the option open of playing b5.} 15.
Rd2 {[%cal Gb1d1] White strengthens his position by doubling the rooks first
before taking any concrete actions.} Re8 {Black continues to wait.} 16. Rbd1
Nc5 17. h4 $1 {Since Black's knight has come to the queenside, White rightly
attacks on the kingside.} h5 {Black cannot allow White to play h5 since it
will be dangerous for Black as White will continue the attack by playing moves
like Qg5-h4 and Ng5.} 18. Ng5 $40 {White immediately made use of the square
that was weakened by Black's previous move.} a5 19. f4 $1 {[%cal Rf4f5,Yg2g4]}
f6 20. Nh3 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Rf8 21. g4 $16 {A few moves ago, the position was
so innocent and now White took over the initiative with simple yet powerful
moves. The rest of the game shows how White managed to succeed with his attack.
} hxg4 22. Bxg4 {[%cal Rh4h5]} e5 23. Rxd6 Qe7 24. Qg3 a4 25. Rd7 Nxd7 26. Rxd7
Qc5+ 27. Kf1 Nd4 28. Nxa4 Qc6 29. Bxd4 Qxe4 30. Bf2 Rfd8 31. Be6+ Kh8 32. Nxb6
Qb1+ 33. Be1 Be4 34. Nf2 Rxd7 35. Nxd7 exf4 36. Qxf4 Bd3+ 37. Nxd3 Qxd3+ 38.
Kg2 Rd8 39. Nc5 Qc2+ 40. Bf2 Qxa2 41. Bd5 f5 42. Ne6 Re8 43. h5 Qe2 44. hxg6 {
Liebert-Horvath 2012 ICCF 1-0} *

