{[#]} 16... Nd7 {This is the kind of middlegame White generally hopes to get
in this pawn structure. Both sides have major pieces and two minor pieces each.
The position is equal, yet not drawish! Black does not have enough resources
to realize the b5 or d5 pawn break. Moreover, he should also be careful before
playing b5 since it could also give White a chance to create a passed pawn on
the a-file after cxb5 axb5 followed by a2-a4. So, Black generally plays normal
moves and waits for White to come up with something. White improves his
position to the maximum before taking any concrete action.} 17. Bd4 {[%cal
Gd3g3] Keeping the option open of playing Qg3 at the appropriate moment and
denying Black from playing Bf6 since the exchange of the dark-squared bishops
would leave the d6-pawn defenceless.} Rfd8 18. h3 {White simply improves his
position.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7a5,Ya5h5] Black's queen was not doing anything on c6
and so he decides to transfer it to a more active square.} 19. Rfd1 Qa5 20. Qd2
{[%cal Rc3d5] Not only creating the threat of Nd5 but also placing the queen
on a better square.} Kf8 21. Qb2 $1 {[%cal Ga1h8]} Kg8 22. a4 {Generally,
White should play a4 only when he does not have any other way to stop Black
from playing b5 since such a move leaves White with a weak b3- pawn. However,
here Black has limited material and so it would be difficult for him to attack
the b3-pawn.} Qh5 {It is already difficult to suggest a useful move for Black.}
23. Ne2 Bf6 {Black decides to swap the bishops.} (23... Bf8 24. f3 $1 {[%csl
Ge4] Defending the e4 pawn!} b5 25. cxb5 axb5 26. a5 $1 $14 {[%csl Ga5,Gb3,Rb5]
That's a typical reaction.}) 24. Rc3 Bxd4 25. Rxd4 {[%csl Rd6]} Qe5 26. Qd2 Nf6
27. Re3 {[%csl Gd2,Gd4,Ge3]} Rd7 28. a5 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7,Gd2][%cal Gd2a5]
Fixing the pawns on the queenside as this pawn is more of an asset for White
rather than a weakness.} Qg5 $2 {A tactical oversight.} (28... g6 {[%cal Gg8h7]
Followed by Kh7 would offer at least a little resistance.}) 29. e5 $1 Ne8 30.
Nc3 $1 {[%cal Re5d6,Yc3e4] Maintaining the pressure along the d-file and
capturing the d6 pawn at the appropriate moment would have sealed the game in
White's favor.} (30. exd6 $6 Rc6 $1 $14 {1/2-1/2 (65) Carlsen,M (2870)-Anand,V
(2775) Chennai 2013 CBM 158 [Szabo,Kr]}) *

