{Black is lacking space and so he naturally decides to exchange some of the
pieces. However, he faces problems despite the reduced material.} 12... Ne5 13.
Rac1 {White simply develops his pieces and strengthens his position.} Bxf3 14.
Bxf3 Qc5 {It is a matter of taste here. White decides to maintain the queens
on the board.} 15. Qe2 (15. Qxc5 {is also possible} dxc5 (15... Nxf3+ 16. gxf3
dxc5 17. e5 Nh5 18. Rd7 $14 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Rd7a7,Rd7h7]}) 16. Be2 {with a
healthy bishop pair}) 15... Rac8 16. g3 {[%cal Gf3g2]} Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Qc6 (
17... b5 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Nd5 $18) 18. Qe2 {Moving the queen away from the
h1-a8 diagonal and also keeping an eye on the b5-square.} Rfe8 19. Rd2 {
[%cal Gc1d1] White gradually increases the pressure by playing natural moves.}
h5 {Black realized that he was threatening to gradually lose the thread so he
retorted to active measures.} 20. Rcd1 {But now White simply captured the pawn!
} h4 21. gxh4 $16 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gf2f3,Gg1h1,Ra1h8,Rg1g8] Unfortunately for
Black, opening up the kingside helps White to launch an attack.} b5 {Black is
desperate for counterplay. However, White is ready to operate on both sides of
the board.} 22. cxb5 axb5 23. Nxb5 Nxe4 24. Na7 $18 {[%cal Ra7c6,Ra7c8] 1-0 
(39) Andreikin, D (2702)-Korobov, A (2667) Minsk 2018} *

