{[#]} 11... b6 {Black is a few tempi down in this hedgehog structure. White
develops his pieces with tempo by attacking the d6-pawn:} 12. Ba3 {[%csl Rd6]
[%cal Ra3f8]} Nc5 {White decides to simplify the position by means of} 13. e5
$1 dxe5 14. Qxe5 Qa7 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black now threatens to play Ncd7 attacking
both the queen and the a3-bishop and so White prophylactically moves his queen
away.} (14... Qxe5 15. Nxe5 {[%csl Ga3,Rc6][%cal Rc3a4,Ra3f8,Ge2f3] leaves
Black with a weak c6-square.}) 15. Qe3 Bb7 16. Ne5 $14 {All of White's pieces
are well placed and Black's pieces lack co-ordination. White will soon
exchange the light squared bishops in order to take control over the c6-square.
} Rfd8 17. Na4 $1 {White gradually increases the pressure by creating multiple
threats.} a5 {Weakens the b5-square. However, it is already difficult to
suggest a better move here.} 18. Bf3 {[%csl Rc6]} Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rc8 20. Bxc5 {
was probably stronger than the text continuation.} (20. Nc3 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 Qc7
22. Bb2 $1 $16 {White managed to win anyway in: 1-0 (30) Artemiev,V (2650)
-Mchedlishvili,M (2618) Kocaeli 2014}) 20... bxc5 (20... Bxc5 21. Nxc5 bxc5 22.
Bxb7 Qxb7 23. Qxc5 $1 $18) 21. Nc3 {[%csl Gb5,Gc6][%cal Rc3b5] leaves Black
with many weak light squares.} *

