1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qe3 Nf6 6. Be2 Bg4 {Black's idea
is to capture on f3 in order to take control over the d4/e5 squares,
especially after a possible c2-c4 by White.} 7. O-O {Our moves are quite
simple and automatic. Here Black has to decide which pawn structure to enter:}
g6 (7... e6 {This allows White to employ a better version of the Maroczy
structure since Black will lose his light-squared bishop and the other bishop
remains passive on the e7-square.} 8. Rd1 {It is recommended to play this move
before moving our queenside pawns and pieces for two reasons. 1. By playing
this move, White puts the rook in opposition to the queen and therefore Black
has to always watch out for e5 tricks. 2. White's kingside rook belongs to d1
anyway, so why not move it right away?} Be7 (8... Qb8 {Moving the queen away
from the opposition with the rook.} 9. c4 (9. h3 $5 $146 Bh5 {Black is
underdeveloped and it encourages White to play concretely in order to force
Black to play the only moves that save his position.} (9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Be7
11. c4 O-O 12. Nc3 $14 {Leaves White with a healthy bishop pair and a strong
centre which gives him an everlasting advantage.}) 10. Nc3 (10. g4 {is also
possible} Bg6 11. Nc3 h6 {transposes to the main line}) 10... h6 {This move
vacates the h7 square since White was threatening to play g4 followed by Nh4.}
(10... Be7 $6 {Black cannot afford to play simple developing moves especially
when White played Nc3 instead of the routine c4.} 11. g4 $1 $16 Bg6 12. g5 Nd7
(12... Nh5 13. Nh4 O-O 14. Bg4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Re3e2]}) 13. Nh4 $16 {
[%cal Ge3g3] Followed by Qg3 and f4-f5}) (10... Bxf3 {Black can claim that he
cunningly stopped White from playing c4. However, White is way ahead in the
development and this factor gives White a better position.} 11. Qxf3 Be7 {
Here the computer recommends} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] Preparing for Black to
castle. If he does not castle, he can play h5 next followed by Qg3. It is
important to note that the bishop on e2 stops Black from playing Nh5 which is
usually the case in such Sicilian type of positions.} O-O 13. g4 {[%csl Re6]
[%cal Gg4g5,Gf3h3,Gh4h5,Gg5g6,Rh3e6] Going for an all-out attack and this
could be dangerous for Black because he does not have the important light
squared bishop anymore which defends the e6 pawn when White plays g4-g5-g6.
Those who like to play such attacking chess are welcome to try this.}) 11. Nd4
Bxe2 (11... Nxd4 12. Rxd4 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Be7 14. Rd3 $1 $14 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ga1d1]
Not only planning to play Bf4 followed by Rad1, but White can also always
shift the rook to the kingside to create attacking chances.}) 12. Ncxe2 Be7 13.
c4 $14 {followed by b3 and Ba3 to pressurise the d6 pawn. Black is denied of
any possible counterplay due to the strong centre.}) 9... Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11.
b3 {That's a typical move.} Bd8 $5 {Instead of remaining passive on e7, Black
decides to move the bishop to a5 or b6.} 12. Qd3 $146 {A necessity.} (12. Na4
$6 d5 $132 {1-0 (33) Harikrishna,P (2743)-Preotu,R (2513) Batumi GEO 2018})
12... Bb6 {Black has moved his bishop from the d8-h4 diagonal and it makes
sense for White now to change his plan by playing} (12... Bc7 13. Bg5 $16) 13.
Bg5 $14 (13. Qxd6 $2 Bc7 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Rg4f3,Rc7h2]})) (8... d5 {
[%cal Rd1d8] Such a gutsy move can be played by someone who is well prepared
or someone who always seeks complications irrespective of the position!} 9. Nc3
d4 10. Nxd4 Bc5 11. Nxc6 $5 {Those who like to play imbalanced positions can
choose this.} (11. Qg3 Bxd4 12. Bxg4 Nxg4 13. Qxg4 Qb6 14. Rb1 Bxf2+ 15. Kh1
$14 Bd4 16. Nd5 $1 $14) 11... Qxd1+ 12. Bxd1 Bxe3 13. Bxe3 Bxd1 (13... bxc6 14.
f3 Bh5 15. Be2 $44 {[%csl Gc6,Ge2,Ge3,Rh5][%cal Gc3a4,Gb2b3,Rg1a7,Gf1a6,Ra6b7,
Rb7c6,Ya4b2,Yb2c4,Ya4c5] Black's bishop will be out of play for some time now
and White will play Na4 followed by b3 to consolidate his queenside by means
of moves like Ba6, Nc5 or Nb2-c4. All these factors give White strong
compensation.}) 14. Nd4 Bh5 15. Ndb5 {[%cal Rb5c7]} O-O 16. Bxa7 $44 {[%csl
Rh5][%cal Gf2f3]}) 9. c4 Qc7 10. Nc3 a6 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 Ne5 13. Rac1 $14 {
1-0 (39) Andreikin,D (2702)-Korobov,A (2667) Minsk BLR 2018}) 8. Rd1 Qc8 (8...
Bg7 $2 9. e5 $16) (8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Bg7 10. c4 Qc7 11. Nc3 Ne5 12. b3 Nxf3+
13. Qxf3 $14 {1-0 (33) Harikrishna,P (2732) -Navara,D (2727) Prague CZE 2018})
9. c4 {We stick to our plan of playing c4 followed by b3} (9. b3 Bg7 10. Bb2
O-O 11. c4 $2 {fails to} Nd5 $1 {[%cal Rh8a1]}) 9... Bg7 10. Nc3 Bxf3 (10...
O-O 11. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] with a typical mini edge for White.}) 11.
Bxf3 $146 (11. Qxf3 Ne5 12. Qg3 Nxc4 13. Bg5 O-O 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 Ne5 $11
{1/2-1/2 (58) Zvjaginsev,V (2642)-Ter Sahakyan,S (2590) Skopje MKD 2019}) 11...
Ne5 12. Be2 {White sacrifices the pawn for the initiative.} (12. b3 {White
should always be careful with playing b3 whenever the rook is still on the
a1-square.} Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Nxe4 {[%cal Rh8a1]}) 12... Nxc4 (12... O-O 13. b3
$14 {leaves White with a healthy bishop pair and a strong pawn mass in the
centre.}) 13. Qd4 Nb6 14. Bb5+ Kf8 (14... Nbd7 $2 15. e5 $1 Nh5 (15... dxe5 16.
Qa4 a6 17. Bxd7+ Nxd7 18. Nd5 $18 {[%csl Gd5,Re7][%cal Rd5b6,Rc1g5,Ya4e8,Rd5e7]
}) 16. Bg5 $18 {followed by Nd5 and White's attack is unstoppable.}) 15. Qb4
$44 {The open c-file, the bishop pair and, more importantly, Black's uncastled
king leave White with a strong compensation.} *

