1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 (4... Nf6 5. Be2 e6 {Black wants to
enter the Hedgehog set up by playing a6, Nbd7, b6.} 6. O-O Be7 7. Rd1 Qc7 $6 (
7... Nc6 8. Qe3 O-O 9. c4 {transposes}) 8. Na3 Bd7 (8... O-O 9. Nb5 $16 Qc6 (
9... Qxc2 $4 10. Nc3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gd1d2,Ye2d3] 1-0 (28) Godena,M 
(2449)-Thybo, J (2525) Skopje MKD 2019}) 10. e5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 $36 Qxc2 12. Rd2
Qf5 13. Nc7 $16) 9. Nb5 Bxb5 10. Bxb5+ Nc6 11. Qe3 O-O 12. c3 {with a healthy
bishop pair advantage.}) 5. Qe3 Nf6 6. Be2 {We always develop our kingside
first before playing on the queenside.} e6 7. O-O Be7 {Although this position
is standard with the queen on d1, there are not many games in this particular
position. However, the ideas are similar to those that we studied in the
example section.} (7... d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Qd2 {[%cal Gc2c4]} Be7 10. c4 Nf6
11. Qxd8+ Bxd8 12. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gf3e5]}) 8. c4 O-O 9. Rd1 {As usual we
play Rd1 before developing our queenside.} Qc7 (9... a6 10. Nc3 Qc7 11. b3 {
transposes}) 10. Nc3 a6 11. b3 Rd8 (11... b6 {Black enters an inferior version
of the Hedgehog as Black's knight belongs to d7 in order to defend the b6-pawn
and not on the c6-square. The main drawback for Black to have the knight on c6
is that White can play Rac1 threatening Nd5 since exd5 is met by cxd5.} 12. Ba3
Bb7 13. Rac1 {[%cal Rc3d5]}) (11... Ng4 12. Qf4 Nge5 (12... Bf6 13. Bb2 Nge5
14. Rd2 {[%cal Ga1d1] followed by Rad1 with a pleasant position for White.})
13. Be3 {[%cal Gf4g3,Ge3h6,Ga1c1,Yc3d5]}) (11... Bd7 12. h3 Rfd8 13. Bb2 Rac8
14. Rac1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Qa5 (14... Qb8 15. Na4 $16 {[%cal Ra4b6]}) 15. Na4 $14
{[%cal Ga4b6] All of White's pieces are well placed. White can gradually
increase the pressure by playing a3 and b4. Black lacks a proper plan due to
the lack of space. In practical terms it is difficult for Black to come up
with something.}) 12. h3 Nb4 (12... b6 13. Ba3 Bb7 14. Rac1 $16 {[%csl Gc1]
[%cal Yc1c8,Yc3d5]}) 13. Rb1 $1 {[%cal Gb1b2,Gb2d2]} Bd7 14. Rb2 Be8 15. Rbd2
Rac8 16. Bb2 $14 {All of White's pieces are well positioned and Black's
typical pawn breaks d5 and b5 are kept under control.} *

