1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qe3 g6 6. c4 Bg7 (6... Bh6 {
One of the extra options for Black when delaying the knight's development to
f6.} 7. Qc3 {[%cal Rc3h8]} Qa5 8. Bxh6 Nxh6 9. Qxa5 Nxa5 10. Nc3 {White has a
risk-free position and Black has to spend a few tempi to bring both the
knights into the game.} Nc6 (10... Bg4 {only helps White.} 11. Nd4 Nc6 12. Nc2
$1 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge1d2,Gd2e3] However, I prefer to keep the pieces since White
has more space.} (12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. c5 $14 {is also possible})) (10... Be6 11.
b3 Nc6 12. Be2 f6 {[%cal Gh6f7,Gg6g5] Black tries to play on the dark squares}
13. Rd1 Nf7 14. Nd4 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge1f2,Gg2g3,Gf2e3]}) 11. Nd5 $1 {White
should play Nd5 in this kind of positions because it is difficult for Black to
kick it away.} O-O 12. Be2 Bg4 (12... Be6 13. Rd1 Rac8 14. h4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal
Gh4h5]} Ng4 (14... Kg7 15. h5 f6 16. Nd4 $14) 15. h5 Nge5 16. b3 $14) 13. Rd1
Bxf3 (13... Rac8 14. Nd4 $1 Bxe2 15. Kxe2 Nxd4+ 16. Rxd4 $14 {[%csl Gd5,Rh6]
[%cal Gb2b3,Gh1d1]}) 14. Bxf3 Kg7 {[%cal Gh6g8,Gg8f6]} 15. O-O Ng8 16. g3 Nf6
17. Bg2 {[%cal Gf2f4] White maintains slight pressure}) 7. Nc3 (7. Be2 Qb6 $1
8. Qxb6 axb6 9. O-O Bg4 $15) 7... Nh6 $1 $146 {Black takes advantage of the
fact that the queen is misplaced on e3. He wants to play f5 in order to trade
the e4 pawn as then the knight could jump to f5.} (7... Nf6 8. Be2 {transposes
to the next chapter}) (7... Qb6 $5 8. Nd5 Qxe3+ 9. Bxe3 {[%cal Rd5c7]} Rb8 {
White has to be precise to gain an edge.} 10. c5 $1 dxc5 (10... Bxb2 11. Rb1
Ba3 (11... Bg7 12. cxd6 exd6 13. Bb5 Bd7 14. Bf4 $1 $16) 12. Nd4 $1 Nxd4 13.
Bxd4 e5 14. Bc3 Bxc5 15. f4 $36) 11. Bb5 Bd7 (11... Nf6 12. O-O-O $14) 12. Rd1
Nf6 13. Nc7+ Kd8 14. Na6 $1 bxa6 15. Bxc6 Kc8 (15... Rxb2 16. e5 $18) 16. Bxd7+
Nxd7 17. b3 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Ra7][%cal Ge1e2,Gf3d2] Black's weak king and the
scattered queenside pawns give White a pleasant edge despite being a pawn down!
}) 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O f5 (9... Ng4 {transposes to the next chapter}) 10. Qd2 $5
{Here I tried various options for White. However, none seem to be satisfactory
except the text move.} (10. h3 f4 11. Qd2 Ne5 $132 {[%cal Gg6g5]}) (10. c5 $5
f4 11. Qd3 dxc5 12. Qxd8 Nxd8 13. Nd5 e5 14. b4 $5 cxb4 15. Bd2 $13) (10. Qd3
$5 Nf7 (10... f4 11. Qd5+ e6 (11... Kh8 12. Qg5 $5 Bg4 (12... Nf7 13. Qxf4 Nfe5
14. Qh4 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Rxf3 16. gxf3 Nd4 17. Kg2 $16) 13. Bxf4 Bxf3 14. Bxf3
Nd4 15. Bg4 Nxg4 16. Qxg4 Qc8 17. Qh4 Qxc4 18. Bg5 $14) 12. Qg5 Qxg5 13. Nxg5 {
White is fine once the queen gets exchanged.} Bf6 14. Nf3) (10... Kh8 11. exf5
Nxf5 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White is fine here}) 11. Be3 e5 12. Rad1 f4 13. Bc1
h5 $1 14. Nb5 g5 15. Nxd6 g4 16. Nxf7 Kxf7 $13) 10... Nf7 (10... f4 11. Qd5+ {
transposes to the above line}) (10... Kh8 11. exf5 Nxf5 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]
Once White develops all of his pieces, the weakness on the light squares [d5
and e6] start to tell.}) 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] Black will end up
in a bad position if he plays normal developing moves and so he is forced to
imbalance the position.} e5 13. Bb2 e4 14. Ne1 Nd4 15. Nd5 Nxe2+ 16. Qxe2 Ne5
17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Rd1 $132 {[%cal Ge1c2,Gc2e3,Gc2d4] If White manages to get
Nc2-e3 or Nc2-d4 without any problems, then he will be on top due to the
better queenside pawn structure and the strong d5 -knight. Black should try to
play energetically to not end up in a worse position.} *

