1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qe3 Nf6 6. Be2 g6 7. c4 Bg7 8. Nc3
O-O (8... Ng4 9. Qd2 Qa5 10. Nd5 Qxd2+ 11. Bxd2 {[%cal Rd5c7]} O-O 12. Bc3 {
with a tiny edge for White.}) 9. O-O Bg4 (9... Be6 10. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b3]} Qa5 {
Stopping White from getting his desired set up.} (10... Qb6 11. Qd2) (10... Ng4
11. Qd2 Nge5 (11... Qa5 $6 12. b4 $1 $16 Nxb4 13. Nd5) 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]}
Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Nd4 14. Bd1 {Black's activity is temporary as White will now
play Bb2 followed by a timely Nd5 and if} f5 15. Nd5 $1 fxe4 16. Bb2 Nf5 17.
Bc2 $14) 11. Qd2 (11. h3 Nd7 {again preventing White from playing b3.}) (11.
Bd2 {is also possible} Ng4 (11... Qc5 12. b3) 12. Qg5 Nge5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14.
Qxe5 dxe5 (14... Nxe5 15. b3 $14) 15. Nd5 {[%csl Re5,Re7,Rf7,Rg6,Rh7]}) 11...
Rac8 (11... Nd7 12. b4 $1 Qd8 13. Nd5 $14) 12. b3 {followed by Bb2 and White
got his desired set up.}) (9... Bd7 10. Rb1 Rc8 11. b3 Ng4 12. Qd2 Nge5 13. Bb2
Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Nd4 15. Qe3 a6 16. Bd1 e6 17. Ne2 Nxe2+ 18. Bxe2 $14 {1-0 (65)
Nevednichy, V (2552)-Drnovsek, G (2384) Aschach AUT 2016}) (9... Ng4 {Black
tries to exploit the fact that White did not play h3.} 10. Qg5 $5 {[%cal Gg5h4]
} Nge5 {Black's typical idea of exchanging the f3 knight to gain access to the
d4-square.} (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qa5 12. Qh4 {The absence of Black's g7-bishop
helps White to launch a decisive attack.}) (10... h6 11. Qh4 g5 12. Qg3 (12.
Nxg5 {is also interesting} hxg5 13. Bxg5 $44) 12... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6h5]} 13. Nd2
{[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Re2h5] Black has overstretched his kingside pawns which
leaves White with a clear target on the kingside.}) (10... Bf6 11. Qd2 $1 {
[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] Now White gets Nd5 with a tempo}) 11. Nxe5 dxe5 {This was
played against me and I managed to get a slightly better position in few more
moves.} (11... Nxe5 $6 12. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gf1d1]}) 12. Be3 {Even though
the computer assesses this position as equal, White's play is easier in
practical terms and Black has to decide about his piece placement and other
strategic factors.} Nd4 13. Rfd1 Bd7 14. Rd2 (14. Bd3 $5 {was probably better})
14... e6 {½- (19) ½ (30) Shyam,S (2505)-Raja,H (2420) Douglas ENG 2018}) 10.
Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b3]} Nd7 11. b3 Qb6 (11... Qa5 12. Bb2 $14) 12. Qd2 {[%cal Gc1b2]
Of course we refrain from exchanging the queens due to the space advantage.}
Nc5 13. Bb2 Qa5 14. Rfd1 $14 *

