1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Bb5 Nf6 (5... a6 {Forcing White
to capture on c6 thus Black gets the bishop pair.} 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. O-O e5 8.
Qd3 Be7 (8... h6 9. Rd1 Qc7 10. b3 Nf6 11. Ba3 c5 12. c4 Be7 13. Nc3 $14 {
1/2-1/2 (54) Frendzas,P (2340)-Grivas,E (2495) ch-GRE (team), Poros GRE 1998})
(8... Nf6 9. Rd1 Be7 (9... Qc7 10. c4 Be7 {transposes}) 10. c4 {[%cal Gb1c3,
Gb2b3,Gc1a3] followed by Nc3 and b3} (10. Nbd2 Be6 11. Nc4 O-O {1/2-1/2 (98)
Paichadze,L (2583)-Gabrielian,A (2490) chess.com INT 2019}) 10... O-O) (8...
Ne7 9. Rd1 {Black is taking time to develop his kingside pieces. Therefore it
makes sense to attack the d6 pawn since Black's king is in the centre making
it more difficult to defend the pawn.} Ng6 10. Na3 f6 (10... Be6 11. Nc4 Bxc4
12. Qxc4 Qc8 13. Ng5 Ra7 14. Be3 Rd7 15. Rd3 $14 {1-0 (36) Delgado Ramirez,N 
(2616) -Muniz,R (2257) Montevideo URU 2019}) 11. Be3 Be6 12. Nc4 d5 13. Nb6 Nf4
14. Qf1 Rb8 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. c4 $14 {1-0 (66) Paichadze,L (2564)
-Mgeladze,T (2374) Poti GEO 2018}) 9. c4 {As usual, White sticks to the plan
of playing c4 and b3.} Qc7 10. Rd1 (10. c5 $5 $146 {Even though the computer
suggests this, I feel it is too early for this pawn break since most of our
pieces are yet to be developed. Moreover, there is no necessity for White to
take such drastic measures as his position is pleasant anyway.}) 10... Nf6 11.
Nc3 O-O {[%csl Gc4,Rc6,Rd6,Ge4,Re5]} 12. h3 {Although Black has the bishop
pair, his pieces do not have proper squares and he lacks a clear plan.} Rb8 13.
b3 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,Gc4,Rc6,Rd6,Ge4,Re5] We have an ideal structure in this
position. White's knight has an outpost on a4 and White's bishop can attack
the d6 pawn. Once White's pieces are well positioned, he should always look
for an opportunity to play c5 to break Black's pawn structure. In order to
stop c5, Black himself pushes the pawn to c5, however, it then weakens the d5
square.} Nd7 14. Ba3 Nc5 (14... Qa5 15. b4 $1 Qxa3 (15... Qc7 16. b5 $16 {
[%csl Yd5][%cal Ra3d6]}) 16. Nd5 Qxd3 17. Nxe7+ Kh8 18. Rxd3 $18 {[%cal Re7c8,
Rd3d6]}) 15. Bxc5 dxc5 {At first it looks weird for Black to enter this
position. However, if given an opportunity, Black would be ready to sacrifice
an exchange by means of Rd8-d4. So, White should avoid such tricks.} 16. Qe3 {
Moving the queen away from the d-file as otherwise, Black would gain a tempo by
playing Rd8.} f6 17. Na4 Qa7 18. Ne1 $16 {[%cal Re1d3] 1-0 (26) Wang Hao (2711)
-Idani,P (2599) Kuala Lumpur MAS 2018}) (5... Bg4 $5 {[%cal Rg4f3] Black's
idea is to double White's f-pawn by capturing on f3. Here our routine idea of
playing c4 is too slow and so we have to exploit Black's move by playing
actively} 6. Nc3 a6 (6... Bxf3 7. gxf3 Nf6 8. Bg5 Nd7 9. Qd2 a6 10. Be2 h6 11.
Be3 e6 12. O-O-O Qa5 13. Kb1 $14 {White has the bishop pair that compensates
for the doubled f-pawn ½-½ (42) Gomila Martí, S (2325)-Václav, J (2383) ICCF
2017}) 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 {[%csl Gc6,Gd6,Ge7] This structure is ideal for Black
when White's pawn is on c2 and not on c4. So we have to play concrete moves
posing one threat after another to claim an edge} 8. Qc4 Qc8 9. Ng5 $146 (9.
Be3 Rb8 10. O-O-O e5 {Black was fine in 0-1 (40) Suarez Uriel, A (2394)
-Fedorchuk, S (2607) Guimaraes POR 2018}) 9... Bh5 (9... Nh6 {The knight on h6
looks weird and we can already stop here claiming that White's position is
pleasant.}) (9... e6 10. e5 $1 {[%cal Rc4g4,Ge5d6] Shattering Black's pawn
structure}) 10. g4 $1 h6 (10... Bg6 11. f4 h6 12. f5 $16) 11. gxh5 hxg5 12.
Bxg5 Rxh5 13. h4 $14) (5... Qd7 {At first sight it looks weird for Black to
play like this. However, the point is that Black's queen is better placed on
c6 and the bishop from c8 can move to g4 or e6.} 6. Qd3 a6 7. Ba4 (7. Bxc6 {
is also possible. However, I do not see the point in helping Black with moving
his queen from the awkward d7 square. Also White can capture on c6 at the
appropriate moment.}) 7... Nf6 (7... e5 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Bg5 b5 10. Bb3 $16 {
1-0 (19) Dourerassou,J (2436)-Sagues Andreu,X (2061) Barcelona ESP 2015}) (7...
b5 8. Bb3 e6 9. a4 $1 Rb8 (9... b4 10. a5 $14 {[%cal Gb3a4,Ra4e8]}) 10. axb5
axb5 11. Nc3 Nf6 (11... b4 12. Nb5 $1 $18 {[%cal Gb3a4,Ra4e8]}) (11... Nb4 12.
Qe2 $16 {followed by e5}) 12. Nxb5 (12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Be7 $11 {0-1 (44)
Norqvist,J (2170)-Tisdall,J (2500) Open, Osterskars 1995}) 12... Be7 13. O-O
O-O 14. c4 $16 {with a healthy pawn up}) (7... e6 8. c4 {Of course!} Qc7 9. Nc3
Bd7 10. O-O (10. Bf4 Nf6 11. O-O Ne5 $11 {0-1 (34) Le Roux,J (2275) -Mrdja,M 
(2380) Open, Cannes FRA 1998}) 10... Nf6 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Rd1 $36 {[%cal
Gc1f4,Ga1c1,Yc4c5,Yc3d5,Rf4b8,Rc1c8] Followed by Bf4 and Rac1. Once this is
achieved then Black has faces multiple threats like c5/Nd5 etc.}) 8. c4 g6 9.
Nc3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. h3 {White has played logical moves till now. Black's
queen is misplaced on d7 which hinders the development of his own bishop on c8.
} Qd8 {Black does not have any other useful moves and had to move the queen
back as a move like Qc7 would be a mistake since he would always have to watch
out for Nd5.} 12. Be3 {White continues to play logical moves} Nd7 13. Qc2 $1 {
Nice prophylaxis.} Nc5 (13... Nde5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Nd5 $14) 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15.
Bxc5 dxc5 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6]} 16. Na4 {[%csl Ga4] In this structure it is always
useful to place the knight on a4 since it not only attacks the c5 pawn, but
also stops black from playing a5-a4.} Qa5 17. Rad1 Be6 18. b3 $16 {[%csl Ga2,
Ga4,Gb3,Gc4,Rc5,Re6] 1-0 (33) Bobykin,K (2336)-Diani,J (2180) ICCF email 2011})
(5... Qa5+ 6. Nc3 Qxb5 (6... Bd7 {It looks strange for Black to play like this.
However, his point is that he stopped White from achieving his ideal pawn
structure by playing c2-c4. But this has come at a cost of an important tempo
for Black as the queen on a5 is misplaced and will have to move again.} 7. Qd3
$14 {Followed by 0-0, Bd2/g5. With simple and logical play White's position
will get better and better.}) 7. Nxb5 Nxd4 8. Nfxd4 Kd8 {Black's point is that
he has gained the bishop pair. However to his disappointment, not only has he
lost the right to castle but also White will place his pawns on c4 and e4 to
restrict the light-squared bishop and the other dark-squared bishop can be
exchanged without any significant issues.} (8... Kd7 {does not change the
character of the position and White has a very pleasant position.} 9. c4 {
[%csl Gc4,Ge4]} e5 10. Nc2 Be7 11. Be3 a6 12. Nc3 Nf6 13. O-O-O b5 {Black
seeks to play actively. However, it has a major flaw} 14. cxb5 axb5 15. f3 Bb7
16. Nb4 $1 $16 {[%csl Gb4] Exploiting the drawback of Black's 13th move. Now
b4 serves as a nice outpost for the knight: 1-0 (56) Destruels Moreno, V (2370)
-Sanchez Carol,J (2049) ICCF email 2012}) 9. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4]} Nf6 (9... Bd7
10. Nc3 e5 11. Nc2 f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Ne3 Bg6 14. b3 Nf6 15. Ba3 Kd7 16.
O-O-O $16 {1-0 (56) Schmдling,M (2221)-Hirsch,H (2222) www.remoteschach.de
2011}) 10. f3 Bd7 11. Bd2 e5 12. Ne2 Bxb5 13. cxb5 h6 14. O-O-O Be7 15. Bc3 Kc7
16. Rd3 $14 {1-0 (39) Zhigalko,S (2668)-Tihonov,J (2472) Minsk BLR 2010}) 6.
O-O Bd7 (6... Nd7 7. Qe3 a6 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. b3 e5 10. c4 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O 12.
Rd1 Qc7 13. Ba3 Rd8 14. Rd3 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1] 1-0 (34) Malakhov,V (2716)
-Olszewski,M (2551) Warsaw POL 2013}) 7. Qd3 a6 (7... g6 8. c4 {transposes to
the next chapter}) 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Re1 e6 (9... h6 10. c4 e5 11. Nc3 Be7 12.
Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4f5] Provoking Black to play g6} (12. Nd2 {0-1 (34) Blomqvist,
