1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 a6 {Preventing White from playing Bb5.} (
4... Nc6 5. Bb5) 5. h3 {One of Black's important plans is to play Bg4 and to
capture the f3 knight in order to take control of the d4-square, hence White's
prevents that idea.} Nc6 6. Qe3 g6 7. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] White's main plan is
to enter the Maroczy structure, thus restricting Black's forces to the maximum.
} Bg7 8. Be2 Nf6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O {This is the critical opening position and
Black has to come up with a plan about his piece placement.} Nd7 {Black not
only intends to transfer the knight to c5, but also he keeps the idea of
exchanging queens under favourable circumstance and also to play f5 to break up
White's centre.} (10... Bd7 {Black cannot afford to make simple developing
moves as he will soon end up in a bind position once White completes his
development.} 11. Rb1 (11. b3 $2 {White should never fall into this typical
opening trap} Nxe4 {[%cal Rg7a1]}) 11... Rc8 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] Followed by
Bb2 and a timely knight jump to d5.}) 11. Rb1 {A typical move, especially when
Black plays Nd7.} (11. b3 {is also possible; however, the next move is more
flexible as it not only defends the b2 square, but also he can push the pawn
to b4 in certain lines.}) 11... a5 {Preventing White from playing b4 and by
doing so he creates an outpost for his knight on the c5-square. However, this
also weakens the b5 square.} (11... Qb6 {allows White to play} 12. Nd5 Qxe3 13.
Bxe3 Nc5 14. e5 $1 {ruining Black's pawn structure}) 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} Nc5
13. Bb2 {So far White has played normal, logical moves and already he is
slightly better due to the strong control in the centre and denying Black good
squares for the pieces.} f5 {Although Black weakens the e6 square, it is the
best practical way to create some counterplay. However, with easy and precise
play, White can dismantle Black's threats.} (13... Bd7 14. Nb5 $16 {with the
idea to exchange Black's only active piece, the g7-bishop, and then the
squares around the king would become very weak.}) 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Rbd1 a4 (
15... Qe8 16. Ba1 $1 {Now White can move his c3 knight. Gradually, the
weaknesses on the light squares will prove to be fatal for Black.}) 16. Ba3 {
Carlsen decides to keep playing simple yet logical moves to sustain the
pressure} (16. Nxa4 {is also possible.} Bxb2 17. Nxc5 Rxa2 (17... Qb6 18. Na4
Qxe3 19. fxe3 Bg7 {with some compensation for Black.}) 18. Rd2 {[%csl Gd2]
[%cal Gd2a2,Gd2d8]} Bd4 19. Nxd4 Rxd2 20. Nce6 Rxe2 21. Qxe2 Nxd4 22. Nxd4 $14)
16... Qa5 17. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Gb5] Exploiting Black's 11th move} axb3 18. axb3 {
[%csl Rb5,Rd5,Re6][%cal Ra3c5] With simple moves White managed to get a
pleasant position and with so many weak squares, Black decided to complicate
the matters by} Qxa3 $5 (18... Bc2 19. Bxc5 dxc5 (19... Bxd1 20. Bb6 $18) 20.
Rd7 $16 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Ra7h7,Ge2d3]}) 19. Nxa3 Rxa3 20. Nd2 {Unfortunately
for Black, two minor pieces for the queen were not good enough to hold the
game as Carlsen, like his usual self, kept playing strong moves one after
another and eventually won the game.} Bd4 21. Qg3 Be5 22. f4 Bf6 23. Bg4 Nd4
24. Kh1 Bc2 25. Rde1 Kh8 26. Re3 h5 27. b4 h4 28. Qf2 Nd3 29. Qg1 Nf5 30. Bxf5
gxf5 31. Nf3 Rc3 32. c5 Bb3 33. Ne1 Bd4 34. Nxd3 dxc5 35. Qf2 Rf7 36. Rc1 cxb4
37. Rxc3 bxc3 38. Qe1 {Carlsen-Gawain Jones 2012 1-0} *

