1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 $5 {This is an interesting move
order against 4.Qxd4} 5. Be2 {Now Black can play Nc6 since it cannot be met
with Bb5} Nc6 6. Qe3 Bg4 {Black is ready to give his bishop for the knight in
order to take control of the d4 square and also to create counterplay along
the dark squares after the possible g6 followed by Bg7.} 7. O-O g6 8. Rd1 $1 {
White threatens to play e5 and so Black is forced to take some decision} Bxf3 (
8... Bg7 9. e5 $16) (8... Qc7 9. c4 Bg7 10. Nc3 O-O (10... Bxf3 {Transposes to
the game}) 11. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] Black is forced to take on f3 at some
point.}) 9. Bxf3 Bg7 10. c4 {[%cal Gc4c5]} Qc7 11. Nc3 Ne5 (11... O-O 12. b3
$14 {White has two bishops and a strong centre, thus depriving Black of any
active play.}) 12. b3 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 {Although Black has managed to eliminate
White's bishop pair he is still under pressure.} O-O 14. Be3 {White changes
the plan by changing the bishop's diagonal so that he now intends to play Rac1
thus reducing the power of the g7 bishop.} (14. Bb2 {is also possible. However,
White's bishop does not do much here and there is a possibility of entering a
major piece ending after the possible Nc3-d5.}) 14... Qa5 15. Rac1 a6 {Black
threatens to play b5 thus creating some counterplay.} 16. Bd2 {[%cal Re1a5]} (
16. a4 {Generally, such a move has to be played only when White does not have
any other way to prevent b5 since this could also weaken the b3 pawn.}) 16...
Rfc8 (16... b5 17. Nxb5 Qxa2 18. Nd4 $1 $18 {[%cal Rd4c6,Gc1a1]}) 17. h3 {
As usual, White improves his position before taking any concrete action.} b5 $6
{Black decides to act first as he does not have useful waiting moves.} (17...
Qh5 18. Qxh5 Nxh5 19. Nd5 {[%cal Rd5e7,Rd5b6]}) (17... Qd8 {[%csl Gd1][%cal
Rd1d8]} 18. e5 $16 {[%cal Gf3b7]}) (17... Qc7 {[%cal Gc1c8]} 18. Bg5 {[%cal
Rg5f6,Rc3d5] Followed by Bxf6 and Nd5}) (17... Qb6 18. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5f6,Rc3d5]}
) 18. Nd5 {White failed to exploit Black's previous move.} (18. e5 $1 dxe5 19.
Na4 b4 20. a3 $16) 18... Qd8 19. Be3 {[%cal Rd5b6]} Nxd5 20. cxd5 Rc3 (20...
Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Rc8 22. Rc6 Rxc6 23. dxc6 Qc7) 21. Rxc3 Bxc3 22. Rc1 Rc8 (22...
b4 23. a4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gh3h4,Gh4h5,Ye3h6] White eliminates his weakness on
the a-file and can now shift his attention to the kingside.}) 23. Qe2 {
Although the pawn structure is symmetrical, White retains pressure due to the
space advantage and the weak c6-square.} Qa5 24. Rc2 Rc7 25. Qd1 {[%cal Gd1c1]}
Be5 $2 (25... b4 26. Qd3 $14) 26. Rc6 $1 Rxc6 27. dxc6 b4 28. f4 Bf6 29. Qe2 e6
30. Qd3 d5 31. exd5 exd5 32. Bd4 Bxd4+ 33. Qxd4 Qc7 34. Qxd5 $18 *

