1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. c4 (5. Be2 {is also possible})
5... Nc6 6. Qe3 g6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 Be6 10. Nc3 Nd7 {[%csl Gg7]
[%cal Gh8a1]} 11. b3 {White's moves are more or less automatic up to this
point.} Qb6 12. Qd2 {White has more space but he is yet to develop his pieces
and so it is premature to exchange the queens.} Qa5 (12... Nc5 13. Bb2) 13. Bb2
a6 {Which rook should come to d1?} 14. Rfd1 {It is better to keep the
queenside rook on a1 since it belongs to b1 or c1.} Rab8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 15. a3
{[%cal Gb3b4]} Nde5 {Black wants to exchange the f3 knight to take control
over the d4-square.} (15... b5 $2 16. b4 {and Black loses the b5 pawn}) 16. b4
Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Qb6 18. Nd5 {A typical move in this structure.} Bxd5 19. Bxg7
Kxg7 20. exd5 Ne5 21. Be2 {[%csl Ga3,Ra6,Gb4,Rb7,Gc4,Gd5,Rd6][%cal Ya1c1,Yc1c3,
Yc3g3,Yg3h3,Yc4c5] This is the kind of position that White is striving for. He
has space advantage and a much better pawn structure. Generally in this kind
of positions, White plays on both sides of the board so that the side lacking
space cannot shift his pieces from one side to another. So here white plays
Rac1 so as to defend the c4 pawn and also help white to play c4-c5. The rook
on c1 also helps White to attack the black king by means of a timely rook
shift along the 3rd rank.} Rbc8 22. Rac1 Kg8 {Black has to make this move
anyway when White places his queen on the a1-h8 diagonal and so he decided to
move it right away.} 23. Rc2 {[%cal Gd1c1,Rc4c5]} Qa7 (23... Rc7 24. Rdc1 Rfc8
25. h4 $40) 24. Rdc1 b6 25. Qe3 $1 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gg1a7,Rf2f4] The queen is
better placed here since it keeps an eye on both the b6 and the e7 pawns.} Rfe8
26. f4 {It is time to kick the knight from the centre.} Nd7 27. Bg4 {Black's
pieces are completely tied down and he has to wait for White to go wrong to
create counter-chances.} Rb8 28. Kh2 $1 {Useful prophylaxis as the king moves
away from the g1-a7 diagonal.} Nf6 29. Bf3 a5 {Black has to do something to
open files as a passive play would lead nowhere.} 30. Qd4 {White now shifts the
attention to the weak e7 pawn by doubling the rooks on the e-file.} Nd7 31. Re1
{[%cal Re1e8]} axb4 32. axb4 Qa4 33. Qc3 Nf6 {White has improved his position
to the maximum and so it is the time to attack the opponent's king.} 34. g4 $1
Ra8 35. g5 Nd7 36. Kg3 $1 {White does not need to hurry with the plan since
Black is out of any productive moves and by playing this move he removes his
king from the 2nd rank and also he defends the f3 bishop in advance.} Qa3 37.
Qd2 {There is no need to exchange the queens as White needs the queen to play
on both sides of the board and Black's queen cannot penetrate into the White's
camp.} Qb3 38. Re3 Qb1 39. Rc1 Qa2 40. Qc3 {Both the White rooks are
controlling all the important squares thus denying Black from entering White's
camp.} Qa7 41. h4 $1 {[%cal Rh4h5]} Rac8 {[%cal Rb6b5]} 42. Qd4 $1 {White pays
attention to the opponent's moves and does not hurry with his plan.} Nf8 43.
Bg4 Rcd8 44. Rce1 {White has succeeded in his plan of doubling on the e-file
and also he intends to play h5 to open the position up even further so that
Black is defenceless.} Qc7 45. h5 {[%cal Rh5h6]} gxh5 {A sad necessity as
otherwise White plays h6} 46. Bxh5 {[%cal Gf4f5]} e5 {Black is desperate to
complicate the game; however, White is ready to face such things.} 47. fxe5
dxe5 48. Rxe5 Rxe5 49. Qxe5 Qxc4 50. Qe7 Qxd5 51. Bxf7+ Qxf7 52. Qxd8 $18 {
The rest of the game does not need any commentary as Hikaru won comfortably.}
Qb3+ 53. Kf2 Qc2+ 54. Re2 Qc4 55. Qd6 Qh4+ 56. Ke3 Qxg5+ 57. Kd3 Qb5+ 58. Kd2
Qg5+ 59. Kc2 Qf5+ 60. Kb2 Qf3 61. Rc2 Qe4 62. Qxb6 Qe5+ 63. Rc3 Qe2+ 64. Ka3
Qe1 65. Qd4 Qa1+ 66. Kb3 Qb1+ 67. Ka4 Qa2+ 68. Kb5 Qe2+ 69. Qc4+ *

