1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 a6 5. Be2 Nc6 6. Qe3 Bg4 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Rd1 {As usual White plays Rd1 first before playing c4.} Nd7 9. b3 (9. c4 {
is also possible}) 9... Rc8 10. c4 (10. Bb2 {is also possible. However, White
decides to postpone the development of the bishop so that he can move to a3 in
order to attack d6 once Black plays e6, and he can go to b2 when Black plays
g6.}) 10... Bxf3 (10... e6 11. Ba3 {[%csl Rd6]} (11. Bb2 {[%csl Rg7][%cal
Gb2h8] is also equally good})) 11. Bxf3 g6 12. Nc3 {White decides to play
simple yet logical chess.} ({However} 12. Bb2 {was stronger} Nce5 13. Be2 Bg7
14. Rd2 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4]} O-O 15. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Ga1d1] Black's knight on e5
is doing nothing and Black has to be constantly worried about White's f4 and
e5 ideas.}) 12... Bg7 13. Rb1 {White yet again decides to postpone the
development of the bishop and moves the rook away from the h8-a1 diagonal.} Qb6
(13... O-O) 14. Nd5 Qxe3 15. Bxe3 {Probably White was counting on this and
this could be the reason for delaying the development of the c1 bishop. A
knight on d5 is always annoying and Black decided to kick it away at the cost
of weakening the d6 pawn.} e6 16. Nb6 Nxb6 17. Bxb6 {White consistently played
simple and logical moves and got a better position out of the opening. He now has
the bishop pair and a clear target in the d6 pawn.} Be5 18. Be2 $1 {[%csl Gc4]
[%cal Gg2g3,Gf2f4,Yb3b4,Ge2c4] Not only intending to play g3 and f4, but also
to defend the c4 pawn once White plays b4.} Ke7 19. b4 {[%cal Rc4c5,Rb4b5,
Ra2a4]} Bc3 20. a3 e5 {[%csl Rd4] Black decides to strengthen the d4-square at
the cost of weakening the d5-square. However, White can always break through
and rip the position apart despite the blockade on d4 due to the strong pawn
mass on the queenside.} 21. Bg4 {It is important to control the c8-square so
that Black cannot attack the c4-pawn.} Ra8 22. Rd5 {[%csl Ga3,Gb4,Gc4,Rd6,Ge4,
Re5][%cal Rb6c7,Rg4c8,Rb6d8,Rc7d6] Now Black is helpless against Bc7 since
both the c8 and d8 squares are controlled by these bishops.} h5 23. Bh3 Nd4 24.
Bc7 Ne2+ 25. Kf1 Nf4 26. Bxd6+ {White easily won the pawn and the rest of the
game does not need any further comments.} Kf6 27. Rdd1 Nxh3 28. gxh3 Bd4 29. f4
Rac8 30. Rxd4 exd4 31. Be5+ Ke6 32. Bxh8 Rxh8 33. Ke2 f5 34. Kd3 fxe4+ 35. Kxe4
Re8 36. c5 Kf6+ 37. Kxd4 Kf5 38. a4 Rd8+ 39. Kc4 Rd7 40. b5 axb5+ 41. axb5 Rd2
42. c6 bxc6 43. b6 Rd8 44. b7 Rb8 45. Kc5 *

